# 🌐 HTTP Protocol

> **Module:** Web Security  
> **Lesson:** Day 3

---

## Introduction

Whenever you interact with a website, your browser and the web server communicate using **HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)**.

HTTP defines a set of rules that allow clients and servers to exchange information over the web.

Every time you:

- Open a webpage
- Log into a website
- Search for a product
- Submit a form

your browser sends an **HTTP Request**, and the server returns an **HTTP Response**.

Understanding HTTP is one of the most important foundations in Web Security because almost every web attack involves modifying or analyzing HTTP traffic.

---

## What is HTTP?

**HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)** is the communication protocol used between a client (browser) and a web server.

It follows a simple request-response model.

```text
Browser
     │
     ▼
HTTP Request
     │
     ▼
Web Server
     │
     ▼
HTTP Response
     │
     ▼
Browser
```

---

## Request-Response Model

Every interaction follows the same pattern.

1. The browser sends a request.
2. The server processes the request.
3. The server sends back a response.
4. The browser displays the result.

Example:

```text
Open https://example.com

↓

Browser sends HTTP Request

↓

Server processes request

↓

Server sends HTTP Response

↓

Browser displays webpage
```

---

## HTTP is Stateless

One of the most important properties of HTTP is that it is **stateless**.

This means:

> Every HTTP request is treated as a completely new request.

The server does **not** automatically remember:

- Previous requests
- Logged-in users
- Shopping carts
- Browsing history

Example:

```text
Request 1

GET /

↓

Server responds

---------------------

Request 2

GET /profile

↓

Server treats it as a new request
```

Because HTTP is stateless, websites use **Cookies** and **Sessions** to remember users.

We'll study them later.

---

# HTTP Request

An HTTP Request is sent by the **client** to the **server**.

Example:

```http
GET /login HTTP/1.1
Host: example.com
User-Agent: Chrome

```

---

## Structure of an HTTP Request

Every request consists of four parts.

```text
┌──────────────────────────────┐
│ Request Line                 │
├──────────────────────────────┤
│ Request Headers              │
├──────────────────────────────┤
│ Blank Line                   │
├──────────────────────────────┤
│ Body (Optional)              │
└──────────────────────────────┘
```

---

## 1. Request Line

The first line of every request.

Example:

```http
GET /login HTTP/1.1
```

It consists of three components.

| Component | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| Method | Action to perform |
| Path | Requested resource |
| HTTP Version | Version of HTTP being used |

Example:

```text
GET

/login

HTTP/1.1
```

---

## 2. Request Headers

Headers provide additional information about the request.

Example:

```http
Host: example.com
User-Agent: Chrome
Accept: text/html
```

Some common request headers are:

| Header | Purpose |
|---------|----------|
| Host | Target website |
| User-Agent | Browser information |
| Accept | Data formats accepted |
| Cookie | Session information |
| Content-Type | Type of data being sent |

---

## 3. Blank Line

A blank line separates the headers from the body.

It tells the server:

> "Headers are finished. The request body starts below."

---

## 4. Request Body

The body contains data sent by the client.

Example:

```http
username=soham&password=hello123
```

The body is commonly used when:

- Logging in
- Registering
- Submitting forms
- Uploading files

---

## Complete HTTP Request

```http
POST /login HTTP/1.1
Host: example.com
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

username=soham&password=hello123
```

---

# HTTP Response

After processing the request, the server sends an HTTP Response.

Example:

```http
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/html

<html>
...
</html>
```

---

## Structure of an HTTP Response

Every response also consists of four parts.

```text
┌──────────────────────────────┐
│ Status Line                  │
├──────────────────────────────┤
│ Response Headers             │
├──────────────────────────────┤
│ Blank Line                   │
├──────────────────────────────┤
│ Body                         │
└──────────────────────────────┘
```

---

## 1. Status Line

Example:

```http
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
```

It contains:

| Component | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| HTTP Version | Protocol version |
| Status Code | Result of the request |
| Status Message | Description of the status |

Example:

```text
HTTP/1.1

↓

200

↓

OK
```

---

## 2. Response Headers

Headers describe the response being sent.

Example:

```http
Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 5420
Server: nginx
```

Some common response headers are:

| Header | Purpose |
|---------|----------|
| Content-Type | Type of content |
| Content-Length | Size of response |
| Server | Web server software |
| Set-Cookie | Creates cookies |

---

## 3. Blank Line

Separates response headers from the response body.

---

## 4. Response Body

The response body contains the actual data returned by the server.

It may include:

- HTML
- CSS
- JavaScript
- Images
- JSON
- XML

Example:

```html
<html>

<h1>Welcome</h1>

</html>
```

The browser reads this content and renders the webpage.

---

# Request vs Response

| HTTP Request | HTTP Response |
|--------------|---------------|
| Sent by Client | Sent by Server |
| Requests data | Returns data |
| Contains Request Line | Contains Status Line |
| May contain user input | Contains requested resource |

---

# Common HTTP Methods

| Method | Purpose |
|----------|----------|
| GET | Retrieve data |
| POST | Submit data |
| PUT | Replace existing data |
| PATCH | Update part of existing data |
| DELETE | Delete data |

We'll study these methods in detail in the next lesson.

---

# Common Status Codes

| Code | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| 200 | OK |
| 301 | Moved Permanently |
| 302 | Temporary Redirect |
| 403 | Forbidden |
| 404 | Not Found |
| 500 | Internal Server Error |

We'll explore status codes in depth later.

---

# Why HTTP Matters in Web Security

Almost every web attack involves HTTP.

Examples:

| Attack | Manipulates |
|---------|-------------|
| SQL Injection | HTTP Request |
| Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) | HTTP Response |
| CSRF | HTTP Request |
| IDOR | HTTP Request |
| Burp Suite | HTTP Requests & Responses |

Understanding HTTP means understanding how web applications communicate.

---

# Key Points

- HTTP stands for HyperText Transfer Protocol.
- It follows the Request-Response model.
- HTTP is stateless.
- Every HTTP request has four parts.
- Every HTTP response has four parts.
- The browser sends requests.
- The server sends responses.
- Login data is usually sent in the request body.
- HTTP is the foundation of Web Security.

